    "summary": "TN sufficient — author's own text does the work",
    "content": "**TN sufficient. No inline \"above-the-phenomenal\" needed.**\n\nI already recommended against the inline rendering in my previous response. The new context strengthens that position: the author's own preceding paragraph does exactly what a TN would do — explains the etymology, reinterprets the directionality, connects 形 to 现象. If the translation of that paragraph is accurate, the English reader arrives at \"the Way is the metaphysical, ritual conduct is the phenomenal\" already understanding that \"the metaphysical\" means \"constructed upon phenomena.\"\n\nThe TN's role shrinks to a brief reinforcement rather than a full explanation. Something like: \"[TN: 形而上 (xing er shang) literally 'above form' — the author's reinterpretation of this etymology is developed in the preceding paragraph.\" Even this may be optional if the translation of the preceding paragraph is clear enough.\n\nThe author's text is doing its own pedagogical work. The translator should trust it."
  }
}
